Abstract:
The behavior and performance of denoising algorithms are governed by one or several parameters, whose optimal settings depend on the content of the processed image and the characteristics of the noise, and are generally designed to minimize the mean squared error $(\mathop{m MSE\kern 0pt}
olimits)$  between the denoised image returned by the algorithm and a virtual ground truth. In this paper, we introduce a new Poisson–Gaussian unbiased risk estimator $(\mathop{m PG\hbox{-}URE\kern 0pt}
olimits)$ of the $\mathop{m MSE\kern 0pt}
olimits$  applicable to a mixed Poisson–Gaussian noise model that unifies the widely used Gaussian and Poisson noise models in fluorescence bioimaging applications. We propose a stochastic methodology to evaluate this estimator in the case when little is known about the internal machinery of the considered denoising algorithm, and we analyze both theoretically and empirically the characteristics of the $\mathop{m PG\hbox{-}URE\kern 0pt}
olimits$ estimator. Finally, we evaluate the  $\mathop{m PG\hbox{-}URE\kern 0pt}
olimits$-driven parametrization for three standard denoising algorithms, with and without variance stabilizing transforms, and different characteristics of the Poisson–Gaussian noise mixture.
